comments.author: @tatter_vroom

comments.text: It used a multiplicitave scoring system based on your placement in each discipline. For example, the gold medalist, Lopez, scored 1st, 4th, and 7th, (1x4x7) for a final score of 28. This put a ton of emphasis on getting first place in one of the three disciplines since a 1 adds nothing to a multiplicitave score. So in that last lead climb from Schubert, every person he passed had a massive impact on their overall final placements.

comments.text:
Flame, you are a brilliant storyteller. I spend a lot of time on YT and so rarely comment. In fact, the last time I was compelled to comment was when I saw your Yuto doc.  That documentary was very touching, but I reserved my praise, thinking: I'm a lifelong skater and I also love the Olympics--that doc was made for me. I'm also a chess player, and a climber, and a snowboarder....I think our hobbies and interests would make a nice venn diagram. The algo gave me "The Fall That Changed Everything," and finally I found this doc. You are a uniquely talented storyteller, and it's complimented by your excellent aesthetic palette. I sense that you tell stories that inspire you and I am just so excited to see what you bring us next.  You should set up a patreon or another way for people to show support. I can't say enough how uniquely great your content is, at a time where there is a lot of great content. 
There's so much interesting, informative, and exciting content on Youtube -- but your storytelling has an X factor that moves people to tears. In EVERY video. And boy do I love to cry. Anyway, you're remarkable, your content is great. Make more. Your sub count is criminally low but I suspect it's only a matter of time before your tipping point comes.
